The Ryzhkov Plan, envisions revitalizing the Soviet economy through a tightly managed program of industrial modernization and targeted investment. Rather than embracing market liberalization, Ryzhkov advocates for increased state coordination, technological upgrading of heavy industry, and selective decentralization to improve efficiency—without undermining socialist planning. He canvasses support within the Party apparatus and technocratic circles, portraying his plan as a “rational alternative” to more radical perestroika.
